Part 1:
- Overview CCGS
	- Input: RGB Images, Instance Masks, Pointmaps for each image
	- For 2 adjacent images:
		- For each pixel (i,j) in image 1:
			- identify the closest pixel in image 2 by minimizing the euclidean distance between pointmaps
		- generate correspondence / mapping function phi from this
		- For instance a in mask 1 and instance b in mask 2:
			- define overlap based on phi (how many pixels of a map to pixels belonging to mask b)
			- convert overlap into a matching cost(1 -> 0% match, 0 -> 100% match)
		- find optimal matching over all instance pairs using hungarian algorithm
			
- Overview Graph-Based:
	- Input: Same (RGB Images, Instance Masks, Pointmaps)
		- optional Input: VGGT Confidence scores, camera poses
	- For each instance out of all images:
		- generate graph node
		- node = (image_index, instance_id)
	- For all image pairs:
		- optional: filter by camera distance
		- restrict to  instance pixels (mask > 0)
		- compute pixel correspondece (like CCGS)
			- optional: discard correspondence if 3D distance above threshold
			- optional: discard low-confidence pixels
	- compute instance-to-instance overlap (like CCGS)
	- convert overlap to matching cost (like CCGS)
		- optional: assign max cost if overlap below threshold
	- Hungarian matching (like CCGS)
	- add graph edge between matched instances
	- count connected components in the graph, each component -> one physical object
		
	- optional filters:
		- discard image pairs with large camera distance (benefits computation effort)
		- discard pixels with low confidence score 
		- discard pixel correspondence if 3D distance above threshold
		- assign max cost to instance match if overlap percentage below threshold



